Hisanaga served under leaders such as {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長}}, {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉}}, and {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康}}. He played a significant role in the {{ill|calendar reform debates of the Tenshō period|ja|天正の改暦}} and later became involved in the administrative and ritual duties of the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|徳川幕府}}.

In {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄}} 4 (1595), Hisanaga was temporarily exiled to {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国}} due to his alleged involvement in political conflicts.

=== Later Life ===
He returned to Kyoto in {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長}} 5 (1600) and regained favor, continuing his work in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮}}. His contributions to court and shogunate rituals, including those for imperial successions and shogunate ceremonies, solidified his legacy.

Hisanaga passed away on {{ill|February 24, 1625|ja|1625年2月24日}}.

== Family and Descendants ==
Hisanaga's descendants continued to play significant roles in the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家}} lineage and in other noble families. However, the direct male lineage of {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明}} is believed to have ended.

