'''Tsuchimikado Hisanaga''' (土御門 久脩) was a {{ill|Kuge|ja|Kugyō|1=Kugyō|12=draft}} (court noble) and {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽師|12=draft}} who lived during the {{ill|Azuchi–Momoyama period|ja|安土桃山時代|12=draft}} and the early {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}. He was the son of {{ill|Tsuchimikado Arihisa|ja|土御門有脩|12=draft}}, the head of the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|12=draft}}. Hisanaga attained the rank of {{ill|Junior Third Rank|ja|従三位|1=Junior Third Rank|12=draft}} and held positions such as {{ill|Non-councilors|ja|非参議|lt=Non-councilor|12=draft}} and {{ill|Head of the Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽頭|12=draft}}.

== Biography ==

=== Early Life ===
Tsuchimikado Hisanaga was educated in {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|12=draft}} (astronomy) and {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|12=draft}} (calendar science) from a young age. In {{ill|Genki|ja|元亀|12=draft}} 3 (1572), he came of age. At 14 years old, he was appointed as {{ill|Head of the Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽頭|12=draft}} on {{ill|December 28, 1573|ja|天正元年12月28日|12=draft}}.

=== Adoption into Kadenokōji Family ===
Hisanaga was briefly adopted into the {{ill|Kadenokōji family|ja|勘解由小路家|12=draft}} as the family lacked an heir. However, after the death of his father in {{ill|Tensho|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|12=draft}} 5 (1577), he returned to the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|12=draft}} and resumed his birthright.

=== Service and Achievements ===
Hisanaga served under leaders such as {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|12=draft}}, {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|12=draft}}. He played a significant role in the {{ill|calendar reform debates of the Tenshō period|ja|天正の改暦|12=draft}} and later became involved in the administrative and ritual duties of the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|徳川幕府|12=draft}}.

In {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|12=draft}} 4 (1595), Hisanaga was temporarily exiled to {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|12=draft}} due to his alleged involvement in political conflicts.

=== Later Life ===
He returned to Kyoto in {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|12=draft}} 5 (1600) and regained favor, continuing his work in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|12=draft}}. His contributions to court and shogunate rituals, including those for imperial successions and shogunate ceremonies, solidified his legacy.

Hisanaga passed away on {{ill|February 24, 1625|ja|1625th year 2月24日|12=draft}}.

== Family and Descendants ==
Hisanaga's descendants continued to play significant roles in the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|12=draft}} lineage and in other noble families. However, the direct male lineage of {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|12=draft}} is believed to have ended.

