Tsuchimikado Hisanaga was educated in {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (astronomy) and {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (calendar science) from a young age. In {{ill|Genki|ja|元亀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 3 (1572), he came of age. At 14 years old, he was appointed as {{ill|Head of the Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽頭|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on {{ill|December 28, 1573|ja|天正元年12月28日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

=== Adoption into Kadenokōji Family ===
Hisanaga was briefly adopted into the {{ill|Kadenokōji family|ja|勘解由小路家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as the family lacked an heir. However, after the death of his father in {{ill|Tensho|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 (1577), he returned to the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and resumed his birthright.

=== Service and Achievements ===
Hisanaga served under leaders such as {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. He played a significant role in the {{ill|calendar reform debates of the Tenshō period|ja|天正の改暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and later became involved in the administrative and ritual duties of the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|徳川幕府|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

In {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 4 (1595), Hisanaga was temporarily exiled to {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} due to his alleged involvement in political conflicts.

=== Later Life ===
He returned to Kyoto in {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 (1600) and regained favor, continuing his work in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. His contributions to court and shogunate rituals, including those for imperial successions and shogunate ceremonies, solidified his legacy.

Hisanaga passed away on {{ill|February 24, 1625|ja|1625th year 2月24日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Family and Descendants ==
Hisanaga's descendants continued to play significant roles in the {{ill|Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} lineage and in other noble families. However, the direct male lineage of {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is believed to have ended.

