Tsuchimikado Hisanaga was educated in {{ill|Tenmondō|ja|天文道|1=Tenmondō (astrology)|lt=Tenmondō|qq= (astrology)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmondō|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenmondō (astrology)|qq=}} (astronomy) and {{ill|Rekidō|ja|暦道|1=Rekidō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rekidō|13=User:Immanuelle/Rekidō|qq=}} (calendar science) from a young age. In {{ill|Genki|ja|元亀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genki|qq=}} 3 (1572), he came of age. At 14 years old, he was appointed as {{ill|Head of the Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽頭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Head of the Onmyōryō|qq=}} on {{ill|December 28, 1573|ja|天正元年12月28日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/December 28, 1573|qq=}}.

=== Adoption into Kadenokōji Family ===
Hisanaga was briefly adopted into the {{ill|Kadenokōji family|ja|勘解由小路家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kadenokōji family|qq=}} as the family lacked an heir. However, after the death of his father in {{ill|Tensho|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tensho|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshō (Momoyama period)|qq=}} 5 (1577), he returned to the {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}} and resumed his birthright.

=== Service and Achievements ===
Hisanaga served under leaders such as {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oda Nobunaga|qq=}}, {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyotomi Hideyoshi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Ieyasu|qq=}}. He played a significant role in the {{ill|calendar reform debates of the Tenshō period|ja|天正の改暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/calendar reform debates of the Tenshō period|qq=}} and later became involved in the administrative and ritual duties of the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|徳川幕府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa shogunate|qq=}}.

In {{ill|Bunroku|ja|文禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunroku|qq=}} 4 (1595), Hisanaga was temporarily exiled to {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Province|qq=}} due to his alleged involvement in political conflicts.

=== Later Life ===
He returned to Kyoto in {{ill|Keichō|1=Keichō|2=ja|3=慶長|ja|慶長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keichō|qq=}} 5 (1600) and regained favor, continuing his work in the {{ill|Onmyōryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Onmyōryō|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang Bureau|qq=}}. His contributions to court and shogunate rituals, including those for imperial successions and shogunate ceremonies, solidified his legacy.

Hisanaga passed away on {{ill|February 24, 1625|ja|1625th year 2月24日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/February 24, 1625|qq=}}.

== Family and Descendants ==
Hisanaga's descendants continued to play significant roles in the {{ill|Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado clan|lt=Tsuchimikado family|ja|土御門家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado family|qq=}} lineage and in other noble families. However, the direct male lineage of {{ill|Abe no Seimei|ja|安倍晴明|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Abe no Seimei|qq=}} is believed to have ended.

